==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Astrolabe
<hw>As"tro*labe</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧s"tr⟦osl⟧*l⟦amac⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>astrolabie</ets>, <ets>astrilabe</ets>, OF.
<ets>astrelabe</ets>, F. <ets>astrolabe</ets>, LL.
<ets>astrolabium</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>'astrola`bon</grk>;
<grk>'a`stron</grk> star + <?/, <?/, to take.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>An instrument for observing or showing the
positions of the stars. It is now disused.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Among the ancients, it was essentially the armillary
sphere. A graduated circle with sights, for taking altitudes at sea, was
called an astrolabe in the 18th century. It is now superseded by the
quadrant and sextant.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stereographic projection of the sphere on the
plane of a great circle, as the equator, or a meridian; a
planisphere.</def> <rj><au>Whewell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Astrolater</ent>⟦br⟧
